<div id="idg_container-1">
<h1>Congratulations!</h1>

<p>
	If you can read this, you have successfully installed indigo.
	These pages are meant to document it and serve as examples of its use. 
</p>
<p>
	For a more in-depth discussion of indigo and its design goals, see the
	<a href="sh@display=main%252Fabout">About</a> page. If you want to start 
	using it, the <a href="sh@display=resources%252Ftutorial">Tutorial</a> provides
	a starting point. Otherwise, the code is the documentation!
</p>
<p>
	Case in point: below is the content of the <code>README.md</code> file&mdash;transformed
	into html and included as a normal part of this page.
</p><h1>indigo</h1>
<p>A somewhat different php framework for generating dynamic web pages. 
Documentation and examples included.</p>
<h2>installation</h2>
<p>Please refer to the <code>INSTALL</code> file for instructions (it&rsquo;s really simple.)</p>
<h2>about</h2>
<p>Having created the static version of a page as a design study, I then 
peppered it with some php to make it a little more flexible (mainly for 
the navigation.) Later I added code to generate dynamic content, for 
example to have a blog-like thing on the main page.</p>
<p>In the end I wanted to have the programming separate from the rest so 
that I could easily change or extend my site. I also wanted to try out 
earlier designs with the same content.</p>
<p>After looking at several existing solutions none of them seemed flexible 
enough, so I decided to consolidate the code I already had into some 
sort of framework.</p>
<p>This is the result.</p></div>
</article>
